The objective of this research was to investigate a novel approach to millimeter-wave imaging that can overcome the hardware and image formation challenges present in existing imaging techniques. The concept explored in this work is called Active Incoherent Millimeter-wave (AIM) imaging, and in contrast to traditional phase-coherent millimeter-wave imaging systems, AIM imaging uses the transmission of incoherent signals to enable the use of very sparse receiving apertures for image formation. The sparse receiving array samples scene information in the spatial Fourier transform domain, rather than the spatial domain typical of traditional imagers. Because of this, we have demonstrated that AIM imaging can produce imagery significantly faster than other millimeter-wave imaging approaches. We have also demonstrated the use of AIM imaging through capturing environmental communications signals, thereby providing a method for passive imaging in electromagnetically-dense environments.



In the course of this research, we have explored and demonstrated the concept of AIM imaging through various system-level experimental implementations, including the following:



- Initial proof-of-concept active Fourier-domain imaging at 5.8 GHz using noise illumination and synthesized apertures;



- Two-dimensional 37 GHz imaging system with improved image formation via redundant calibration techniques;



- New experimental approaches for measuring the spatio-temporal coherence of signals for AIM transmitter array design and characterization;



- A high-speed 38 GHz two-dimensional imager capable of producing images at 652 frames per second, more than an order of magnitude faster than any reported millimeter-wave imaging system;



- A 38 GHz two-dimensional AIM system using non-cooperative 5G signals in the environment in order to perform imagery.



